SIMPLE: sordid
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sordid
<hw>Sor"did</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sordidus</ets>, fr. <ets>sordere</ets> to be filthy or dirty;
probably akin to E. <ets>swart</ets>: cf. F. <ets>sordide</ets>. See
<er>Swart</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Filthy; foul;
dirty.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>sordid</qex> god; down from his hoary chin⟦br⟧
A length of beard descends, uncombed, unclean.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Vile; base; gross; mean; <as>as, vulgar,
<ex>sordid</ex> mortals</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To scorn the
<xex>sordid</xex> world.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Meanly avaricious; covetous; niggardly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He may be old,⟦br⟧
And yet <qex>sordid</qex>, who refuses gold.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J.
Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sordidly</ent>⟦br⟧
